Other than being used to nurture talent,  it is also a major platform for addressing social and economic issues facing young people. Retired football stars often meet their peers to reminisce  during Koth Biro tournaments.
Former Kenyan international defender Charles Handas, who played for Gor Mahia, grew up playing in the tournament. After learning the ropes, he later took over as the tournament’s organiser, making it a key fixture for Kenyan Premier League players during the off-season.
Handas served as chairman and organiser of the tournament till his death in 2017. The current leadership has kept the founders’  vision for youth football alive. 
This year,  organisers face the unique challenge of staging the tournament in a Covid-19 year.
The tournament, which had reached the last 16 stage, is on hold and will continue in January. 
But Nairobi County and Starehe Constituency leaders either do not share in the vision of the founders of the tournament, or they have chosen to turn a blind eye to the condition of Ziwani grounds, which alternates from being bumpier than the moon’s surface during dry season, to a muddy pool during rainy season.





Gogo Boys FC striker Hillary Shirao in a previous football match at Woodley Grounds in Kibra, Natiobi.
Photo credit: Pool |


The equally popular Dagoretti Super Cup where Kenya’s all-time top scorer Dennis Oliech has been a regular participant as player and mentor, was postponed this year due to lack of sponsorship, a manifestation of adverse effects of Covid-19.



