Many other off-season tournaments such as the annual Gogo Youth Sports tournament in Siaya County,  were either postponed either due to lack of funding, or lack of capacity to comply with health protocols to ensure safety of players.
When I spoke to him, Gogo Youth tournament coordinator, Nick Otieno, was a crestfallen man.
He has had to postpone the off-season tournament due to lack of a sponsor. His team also lacks capacity to organise a tournament in line with Ministry of Health protocols. But he is unbowed.
He plans a bigger and better tournament next year and for a good measure, he plans to take former Kenyan internationals Peter Dawo,  John “Bobby” Ogola and Tobias Ochola to the village that gave Kenya striker Steve Odiaga. 
The talent and energy on display in off-season tournaments make them worth the time. Young people get to showcase their talent while using their energies productively and entertaining people. And while at it, there is a token of appreciation.
Such off-season football tournaments have been a defining feature of December holidays. But the coronavirus pandemic has reduced the steady flow of such tournaments to a trickle. 
During the few tournaments that are held, organisers look anxiously behind their shoulders.



